<br>
I'll start out by saying I'm a 59 paladin, and also have a 58 monk...I have numerous other characters as well and have played every class (except beastlord) to a certain degree.<br>
<br>
Now, regarding the petition....I will agree that in most every situation I can think of, the druid is considered a secondary healer, even *the* secondary healer of choice.  Your petition seems to fail to remember this point.<br>
<br>
A druid is not supposed to become a primary healer...at least not by default (they can function as such in many cases).  If you consider that you are a backup healer to a cleric, you should be able to handle filling in as needed no matter how many hit points the melee (based on the examples, I have to assume you are meaning &quot;warrior&quot;) has.<br>
<br>
Too often I've seen a 60 druid cast that heal just in time to save the warrior from going down and giving the cleric enough time to get CH off...<br>
<br>
Why do you compare an &quot;average level 60 druid&quot; with shamans with torpor (not what I would call &quot;average&quot;)?  Sure that shaman can heal 1200 hp over 24 seconds, but whoever just got healed for that is slowed AND snared...not always benefits to the person you are trying to heal.<br>
<br>
You also try to compare this to the paladin group heal?  Just how often is *that* useful?  Sure, it's a level 58 spell, and in places like the HoT in ToV it's very handy fighting AE mobs that are hurting your entire group...but otherwise?  unused...or IF used, it's not doing max healing since very few people in the group are hurt.<br>
<br>
Yes, last night in HoT the druid who was primary healer in our group wished he could heal like I was doing (Healing Wave of Prexus).  However, if a cleric had been in the group, his role would likely have been filling in the gaps while the cleric used his heal over time on group members, and I could have paid more attention to melee'ing.<br>
<br>
You compare a druid using 2000 mana to heal 4,400 points of damage whereas a cleric can heal 1,500 for 250 mana.  However, this is rather biased as a druid should, by your petition, not be required to heal 4,400 on one person.  Let me turn the tables on you slightly.  Remember:  focus = druid as a secondary healer.  Druid can heal ~1000 points in 5.5 seconds for 400 mana.  No shaman or paladin or cleric(!) can heal that many points on a single target in that speed (clerics can come close though with Divine Light).<br>
<br>
You state:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Druids are finding themselves in a position of having to use over half of their mana pool over a very long period of time to heal a single caster or priest, let alone a melee class.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Again you are forgetting that a druid is a secondary healer, not a primary.  This would be more relevant if your role was as a primary healer...if you are fighting for that position, then please make it clear in the petition.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Druids are the class most called on to be secondary healers. Paladins are mainly a melee class. Shamans are usually busy with buffs, slows, and debuffs. Yet Druids find themselves behind both classes in healing ability.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I will never compare myself as ahead of a druid in healing ability.  If a druid thinks I have more healing ability, that druid doesn't know how to play their class.  (remember:  my mana pool is *trivial* compared to a druid.  I think my wisdom is regularly around 110 - 120 based on what I'm wearing.)<br>
<br>
Regarding your points...<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> First, we would ask Verant to remove the 10% serverside healing penalty for all non-cleric healers. We wholeheartedly agree with the 5% bonus that clerics receive, but the penalty has outlived its usefulness. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I'm indiffirent to this one.  I don't see it making that much of a difference.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 1) Change the duration on Nature's Recovery from three minutes to 24 seconds and remove the recast time.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->This would be too powerful as it would bring you with a spell that's even more powerful than what clerics have.  Celestial elixer is ~1000 hp for 300 mana.  Again another example sounding more like you want to take over the role of primary healer instead of a secondary one.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 2) Give Druids a group heal—something along the lines of 880 hitpoints healed per member for 900 mana.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->/boggle?  Clerics' Word of Restoration is a 750 group heal for 900 mana....<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 3) Give Druids a larger direct heal. Nature's Touch is insufficient for our current needs; the damage-per-second output of mobs has far surpassed the ability of Nature's Touch to keep even ourselves healthy, much less an entire group.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Again, not sure how this fits in with an assumption of being a secondary healer...<br>
<br>
I like the idea of druids having a single-target version of PotG.  This makes amazing sense!<br>
<br>
I also like the idea that neither Aegolism or PotG overwrite each other....it would save a lot of headache.<br>
<br>
Your epic is your own <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   Not going to touch that one...I do know some epics are more effective than others and a variety of &quot;fixes&quot; would make sense. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> This brings us nicely to our third concern: DoTs. Druids don't receive an upgrade to damage-over-time spells after level 53. We would ask for an upgrade to Winged Death—something along the lines of 1950 damage over 50 seconds at level 58 or 59.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Just curious...why?<br>
<br>
Regarding teleports...you mention that evac off of luclin is the only way to remove from danger.  Don't forget you do have the ability to succor which generally does end up in a safer point of the zone... With the theory that druid ports are somewhat tied to druid locations, I don't understand how it would make roleplaying sense to port on Luclin.  A wizard's port to the Nexus makes sense in so far as there are wizard portals there (the structure).<br>
<br>
The cold debuff line makes sense, since you do have a fire debuff line.<br>
<br>
Good luck with your petition!<br>
